turns: Hillary Clinton's security detail arrived at a fruit processing company in Iowa with an added vehicle, a second Scooby van. The van is visually identical to Clinton's original Scooby van, but has blue and white plates of a different design. The Secret Service uses decoy vehicles, such as identical cars or helicopters, to create confusion and discourage potential attackers. The use of decoy vehicles is not uncommon for high-profile individuals, such as former presidents and presidential candidates. Clinton's constant protection is provided by the Secret Service at taxpayers' expense, as she is a former first lady and not because of her service in the U.S. Senate or State Department.

A mother of six in Georgia has lost her rented condo to a fire and is now homeless with her children. She is asking for help to find a permanent home and has started a GoFundMe page to raise money. She has been turned away from shelters because they cannot accommodate all of her children.The

An Australian couple who entered into a surrogacy arrangement in India were aware that the baby boy would be left stateless due to Indian laws, according to newly released documents. The couple, from New South Wales where surrogacy arrangements are illegal, traveled to India in late 2012 and sought citizenship for a baby girl but told consular staff they would be leaving her twin brother behind because they could not afford him. The couple reportedly told staff they wanted a baby girl to "complete their family." The Australian man told consulate staff he would be giving the boy to some friends in India "who were unable to conceive a child." The couple was told the boy would be left stateless if they followed through on plans to abandon him, because India does not recognize surrogate children as citizens. The documents also reveal that consular staff had concerns that the boy may have been sold, and that any adoption would be deemed invalid under India's Hindu Adoption Act. The case is similar to the recent baby Gammy case, where a baby was born in Thailand to a surrogate mother and only the twin sister was brought back by the Australian parents.

Kecil, a one-year-old orangutan, was rejected by his natural mother and two surrogate mothers before being taken in by Maggie, a 53-year-old orangutan at Chicago's Brookfield Zoo. Maggie has raised four of her own children and one surrogate child before, and she and Kecil have formed an inseparable bond. Kecil will make his first public appearance this weekend and will be on display for two-hour slots between 10am and midday. Keepers say that Kecil has learned to rely on Maggie for comfort and guidance, and the two have become close friends.

Javier Pastore, a star player for Paris Saint-Germain, has dismissed Eric Cantona's claim that he is the greatest footballer in the world. Cantona had praised Pastore for his creativity and ability to make surprising passes, but Pastore believes that Lionel Messi and Cristiano Ronaldo are a class above him. Pastore scored a brace in PSG's win against Nice on Saturday, and they will face Barcelona in the second leg of their Champions League tie on Tuesday, needing to overcome a 3-1 deficit to advance to the semi-finals.

Amanda Burleigh, a midwife at Leeds Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust, has successfully campaigned to change NICE guidelines on cord clamping. She argued that clamping the cord within seconds of birth, as has been the practice since the 1950s, was unnatural and lacked evidence. Burleigh and a group of medics amassed evidence that immediate cord-clamping could be harmful, depriving babies of a third of their blood stock and raising the risk of iron deficiency anaemia. NICE has now changed its guidelines to state that doctors and midwives should not routinely clamp the cord earlier than one minute from the birth of the baby, and the cord should be clamped within five minutes, but left longer if the mother requests. The change means mothers get the chance to hold their babies for a moment while still connected to them. Burleigh faced resistance from colleagues who questioned her challenge to medical protocol, but she felt a "moral duty" to do so. Dr David Hutchon, who retired in 2018, also supported the campaign and said hospitals had blindly clamped and cut within seconds of birth for decades.

French President Francois Hollande has vowed to "show no mercy" if French peacekeepers in the Central African Republic are found guilty of raping hungry children in exchange for food. The French defence ministry has denied covering up the scandal following revelations it was made aware of the allegations in July last year when it received a leaked UN report on the subject. The ministry said it immediately launched a probe into the case when it received the news, sending investigators to the former French colony on August 1. The abuse reportedly took place at a centre for displaced people near Bangui airport between December 2013 and June 2014. A French soldier taking part in 'Operation Sangaris' stands guard at the Boali church as people sit on the floor. A UN employee accused of the leak, Anders Kompass, turned the report over to French authorities because his bosses had failed to take action and has since been suspended. The violence in the Central African Republic has largely pitted the Christian majority against mainly Muslim Seleka rebels who led the March 2013 coup against former leader Francois Bozize.

A shocking video has emerged of a two-year-old dead boy being held during a resurrection ceremony at a Texas church. The pastor's wife, Aracely Meza, was arrested and charged with injury to a child by omission. The boy's mother reportedly believed he was possessed by demons. The ceremony lasted for hours and involved Meza using oils and praying while trying to bring the boy back to life. The home where the ceremony took place was not registered to operate as a church. An investigation is underway involving both state and federal authorities.

John Higgins and Graeme Dott led the Scottish charge at the Betfred World Championship, with Higgins winning 10-5 against Robert Milkins and Dott winning 10-8 against Ricky Walden. Higgins is feeling relief and pride after beating Milkins, who he had lost his last four matches to, and is daring to dream of a fifth world title. Dott is a proven Crucible class act and champion in 2006, and is also through to the second round.The

Barcelona players Neymar, Dani Alves, and Adriano celebrated a hard-fought victory over Celta Vigo in La Liga with a matching denim outfit, but their choice of attire was questionable. The trio played a crucial role in the win, which saw Barcelona return to the top of the league. Despite their poor performance throughout the match, the team managed to secure the three points thanks to a winning goal from Jeremy Mathieu. The Frenchman praised his defensive partner Gerard Pique for his impressive display against a tough opposition.

Jose Mourinho is planning to sign Atletico Madrid midfielder Koke this summer, according to reports in Spanish newspaper AS. The Chelsea boss is said to be willing to offer second-choice left-back Filipe Luis as part of a deal to sign the highly-rated Spaniard, who has a £50million release clause. Koke, an Atletico academy graduate, was instrumental in the club's run to the Champions League final last season and has been a key player for Diego Simeone's side this season. Chelsea's midfield has struggled at times this season, and Mourinho is reportedly looking to add to his options in the middle of the park.

Tom Ballard, a renowned climber, plans to climb K2, 20 years after his mother, Alison Hargreaves, died while descending from the same peak. Ballard, who was just six years old when his mother died, has set his sights on the summit of K2, which is considered more difficult to reach than Mount Everest. His mother was a revered figure in the climbing world and was only the second person to climb Everest without sherpas or bottled oxygen. Ballard's decision to climb K2 has been met with mixed reactions, with some praising his bravery and others criticizing his decision to follow in his mother's footsteps.

A consortium of companies has claimed that there could be up to 100 billion barrels of oil worth trillions of pounds in the Weald Basin area of England, which could meet up to a third of Britain's oil demand within 15 years. The area, dubbed "Britain's Dallas," is located across Surrey, Sussex, Hampshire and Kent. UK Oil & Gas Investments, which has a 30% stake, said 'cutting-edge' data suggested the oilfield holds 158 million barrels per square mile – equating to 100 billion barrels across the basin. However, industry experts remain sceptical of the claims, and some warned that only a fraction of the Weald Basin oil may be accessible for extraction. Fracking could be required to retrieve significant volumes.

The British Veterinary Association (BVA) has withdrawn its support for the shooting of free-running badgers in controversial pilot culls and instead recommends trapping the badgers in cages and then shooting them. The BVA still supports badger culling to tackle tuberculosis in cattle. Animal welfare campaigners have welcomed the news but criticized the BVA's ongoing support for cage-trapping and shooting. The Environment Secretary has promised to roll out more culls across the country if the Conservatives win the election, and criticized Labour for pledging to give up on culling. The first two years of culling in Somerset and Gloucestershire have not demonstrated conclusively that controlled shooting of free-running badgers can be effective and humane.

Modern technology is supposed to make our lives easier, but it often creates more pitfalls. Smartphones and social media can cause problems on dates, such as checking the phone at the table, taking photos of food, and changing relationship statuses on Facebook. To avoid embarrassment, Blu e-cigarettes suggest leaving conversations about dating apps to friends, keeping phones off the dining table, and not updating relationship statuses immediately. They also suggest keeping it offline, moving the chat to a call if it goes well, and not bragging about matches on Tinder. Additionally, they advise against recording the date with Google Glass and not assuming the date will find everything funny.

Tottenham Hotspur will be without Kyle Walker and Hugo Lloris for their home match against Aston Villa due to injuries, while Jan Vertonghen is a doubt. Aston Villa will also be without Alan Hutton, Ashley Westwood, Scott Sinclair, and Carles Gil due to injuries, but Aly Cissokho could return. Tottenham is favored to win the match, with odds of 4/7, while Aston Villa is at 5/1. Tottenham has won their last five PL meetings with Aston Villa and Aston Villa has scored just six goals in their last 12 Premier League matches against Tottenham. White Hart Lane is the highest scoring stadium in the Premier League this season.

A mother who had to make the heartbreaking decision to give birth to her sick baby at just 20 weeks, had her wedding dress redesigned so her tiny daughter could be buried in it. The mother and father of Annabelle, who was born weighing just 290 grams at Canberra Hospital and her distraught parents were able to cradle her in the short five minutes she survived, contacted Angel Gowns, a not-for-profit organization that turns donated wedding gowns into outfits for babies who die too soon. The organization delivered Annabelle's dress on the day she was born and the mother dressed her so the family could spend time with her before she was buried. Angel Gowns created a replica dress for the family to have in their house and the mother looks at it every day to remember her daughter. Angel Gowns currently donates outfits to more than 80 hospitals and funeral homes across Australia and deals directly with families like the Cox's, as well as a number of different children charities. To donate your wedding dress or volunteer with Angel Gowns, visit [www.angelgownprogram.com.au](http://www.angelgownprogram.com.au).

A black police constable, Ronnie Lungu, has won a race discrimination case against Wiltshire Police after they did not promote him due to the colour of his skin. The employment tribunal ruled that the Zimbabwe-born officer was unlawfully discriminated against on grounds of race and that the force had singled him out as a 'marked man' solely due to his race. The force has been ordered to take steps to tackle discrimination and better educate senior members of staff in how to deal with complaints. The force has denied the claims but has said it will learn lessons from the case.

A father taught his newborn daughter how to suck a plastic water bottle and filmed it for YouTube. The video has been viewed over 190,000 times and many viewers found it cute and adorable. The father was impressed by his daughter's attention and ability to copy him.

A collection of rare photographs taken in the 1850s of Bristol, England, has surfaced and is expected to fetch up to £30,000 at auction. The albumen prints, made in the 1870s from the original paper negatives of the early 1850s, show the city's historic centre, including St Mary Redcliffe church, High Street, and Broad Quay. The Fourteen Stars Tavern, which was later replaced by The Bristol Brewery Georges, is also featured in the collection. The images provide a glimpse into the past, as many of the buildings pictured have changed dramatically over the past 160 years. Some areas, such as St John's Gate, have remained largely unchanged, while others, like High Street, have undergone significant transformations. The collection also includes a picture of Sleep Street, which is believed to have been taken shortly before the Fourteen Stars Tavern was knocked down.

A pro-Ukip businessman, Harvey Boulter, who forced Liam Fox to resign as Defence Secretary, is trying to defeat two Tory candidates, one in Somerset and the other in Tonbridge and West Malling, Kent. Boulter is spending £30,000 on each candidate in a vendetta against them, as the High Court judge who awarded Fox a six-figure sum in damages after he sued Boulter for libellous remarks made on Sky TV is the father of one of the candidates. Boulter said that his actions are a form of revenge for the court case.

A six-year-old Aston Villa fan named Charlie Pye applied for the job of manager after Paul Lambert was sacked. Although he missed out on the job to Tim Sherwood, Sherwood wrote Charlie a letter congratulating him on his credentials and offering encouragement. Charlie is the captain of his local team, Norton Lindsey, and had suggested appointing his parents as assistant managers. Sherwood also mentioned Charlie's appointment as captain in his letter.

Atletico Madrid defeated Cordoba 2-0 with goals from Antoine Griezmann and Saul Niguez to move above Valencia in the race for the third Champions League spot. Valencia have a chance to reclaim third place with a win against Villarreal on Sunday. Real Madrid, who are four points behind leaders Barcelona, host Granada on Sunday. Sevilla, the only unbeaten team at home in La Liga, beat Athletic Bilbao 2-0 to stay in fifth place.

An 18-year-old mother-of-one from Castle Donington, Derbyshire, died after taking M-Cat at a house party in Tamworth. Abby Swinfield was rushed to Good Hope Hospital in Sutton Coldfield, where she was placed in a coma, but died a week later. Her cousin claims that her drink was spiked, and a 20-year-old girl has been arrested on suspicion of supplying Class B drugs. Swinfield's mother said she was devastated and that her daughter had suffered two heart attacks before dying of multiple organ failure. Swinfield had a three-year-old son, and her cousin said that he keeps asking for his mother.

A playground in Tokyo has been found to have dangerously high levels of radiation, which has raised concerns for the health of children in the area. Soil underneath a slide at the park showed radiation readings of up to 480 microsieverts per hour, nearly half the recommended annual limit of exposure for a person. The radiation could be coming from something buried underneath the park, and authorities have cordoned off the area. Japan has seen heightened concern over radiation since the 2011 Fukushima disaster, and thousands of people are still living in temporary shelters unable to return home near the nuclear plant. A drone with a small amount of radiation was also found on Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe's office building this week.

Amir Khan believes that Kell Brook has called him out for a payday, as Brook has only faced one decent opponent in his career and is not a big name in the UK or the US. Khan has reiterated his intention to fight Brook within the next 12 months, but claims that Brook is not a big enough name to face the world's biggest names like Manny Pacquiao and Floyd Mayweather Jr. Khan also denied that he will fight Chris Algieri next month, claiming that there are "some more options on the table."

A Dallas architect has transformed 14 shipping containers into a stunning modern three-bedroom home, named PV14. The home boasts a 40ft long swimming pool, a 1,400 sq ft roof deck, and a 360 degree view of White Rock Lake and downtown Dallas. The designers wanted people to know what they were standing in when they stepped into the home, so they left the ceilings exposed and the shipping container gates unpainted. The house's walls are made of sheet rock, and columns had to be placed around the house to restore structural integrity to the materials. The most striking use of the containers is the two-story, glass-paneled tower that overlooks and mirrors the shape of the house's long, slim pool. The upstairs levels are outfitted with maple wood floors to complement the views of the nearby park and lake, and deep porches protect the home from direct sunlight while still allowing natural light to seep in. The couple found the perfect spot for their home on one of the highest elevations in the city, offering one of the best views. After more than two years of design and construction, they are finally preparing to move into their new home.The

Jordan Ibe is set to sign a new five-year contract with Liverpool by the end of the week. The 19-year-old has agreed terms on a deal that will keep him at Anfield until 2020. Ibe has made a notable impact in his eight appearances since returning to Liverpool in January, and he is expected to return to the team this weekend against West Brom. Liverpool are also close to finalizing extensions for Martin Skrtel and Jon Flanagan, and they recently agreed a new three-year shirt sponsorship deal with Standard Chartered worth around £30million a year.

Rik Mayall, the comedian and actor, died suddenly last June aged 56 and failed to leave a valid will to deal with his £1.2 million estate. This could leave his family with a large inheritance tax bill as his personal estate would be divided according to Government intestacy rules. His children would be automatically entitled to a share of his net estate of £1,192,701 after funeral and legal expenses, meaning they could inherit an amount liable for inheritance tax. Mrs Mayall would be due to receive £250,000 plus all his ‘chattels’, which would include any personally owned cars, furniture, ornaments, books and jewellery. Mayall’s family could seek to avoid the tax by drawing up a deed of variation to split up his estate, reducing any sum left to the children so it was below the tax threshold.

Air India has been evacuating people from Yemen during a small window when Saudi planes are not bombing the city. The flights are going to Djibouti, and some evacuees are fleeing on boats at port cities such as Aden. People are leaving behind much more than luggage. The Houthi rebels control Sanaa, including the airport, but the Saudis are bombing the city and thus control air access in a way, so getting people out requires coordination. The scene of people scrambling onto the airport tarmac and boarding the plane with carry-on luggage has been repeated in recent days. Some passengers were already fast asleep, exhausted by the push to get out of Yemen.

An Italian priest has been sacked from a religious order in Taranto after allegations surfaced that he took part in gay orgies with a Swiss Guard. The priest was reportedly dismissed after an online lover contacted the church authorities with a dossier containing alleged evidence of sex with prostitutes, role play, and explicit gay web chats. The priest allegedly favored sexual role-play scenarios in which his lover played the disciple Judas Escariot and had to atone for his betrayal of Jesus by becoming his slave. The diocese confirmed that the priest had been dismissed but claimed there were no other prelates involved. This is just the latest sex scandal to engulf the Vatican.

Another study has found no link between the MMR vaccine and autism, even among children with older siblings with autism. The study, published in the Journal of the American Medical Association, analyzed data from about 95,000 young people and found no association between MMR vaccination and increased autism risk. The study also found that vaccines had no effect on autism risk, whether or not a sibling in the family was diagnosed with autism. The study's lead author, Anjali Jain, said the data is clear and that the only conclusion that can be drawn from the study is that there is no link between MMR and the development of autism in children.

A new report by Human Rights Watch has revealed that ISIS fighters have been kidnapping women and children, particularly Yazidi, as young as eight, forcing them to marry and convert to Islam, and repeatedly raping them. The study found that the actions of ISIS amount to war crimes. The report collected the accounts of 20 women and girls who escaped from ISIS, which shows a system of organized rape and sexual assault, sexual slavery, and forced marriage. The survivors' stories come as United Nations investigators found evidence that ISIS is committing genocide against the Yazidi minority in Iraq. The report highlights brutal ISIS attacks on the Yazidis, separating out men and boys over the age of 14 to be executed, and using child soldiers. The women and girls were abducted as the "spoils of war." The report calls for better support for children and women who survive such attacks, including psycho-social treatment, but there is a reluctance in the community to accept it.

A shooting at Wayne Community College in Goldsboro, North Carolina, left one person dead on Monday morning. The alleged shooter, Kenneth Stancil, a former student who did not graduate from the college, entered the building at 8am and fired one shot, killing a long-time employee of the print shop. Stancil is described as white, approximately 5'11", with a goatee, and a tattoo over his left eye. A warrant for his arrest has been issued, and he is considered extremely dangerous. The college was on lockdown, and students were evacuated building by building as SWAT teams searched the campus. The lockdown was lifted as of about 10.30am ET.

The new chief executive of Rotherham council could be paid up to £40,000 more than the outgoing boss due to "negative publicity" from the grooming scandal. The council will now offer up to £200,000 to candidates, rather than the £160,000 enjoyed by former chief boss Martin Kimber. The rest of the cabinet resigned in February after a Government report said the council was "not fit for purpose" and "in denial" about exploitation, mainly of white girls by men of Pakistani origin. HR chief Phil Howe said additional incentives may be necessary due to recent negative publicity, but Councillor Caven Vines, leader of the Ukip group, is uncomfortable with the idea.The

Cesc Fabregas will wear a protective face mask made by the Ortholabsport in Milan to protect his broken nose. The mask is branded with Fabregas' initial and squad number 'C4' and was made by orthopedic center's craftsmen Stefano Duchini and Lucilla Pezzoni. Fabregas travelled to Milan on Tuesday with Chelsea medical director Paco Biosca to have the mask fitted. He suffered the break during Chelsea's win over Stoke City at the weekend, but played on for the entire 90 minutes. Chelsea captain John Terry also wore a protective face mask after fracturing a cheekbone in 2007, and Fernando Torres wore a mask during his time at Chelsea. Fabregas could be ready to play against Queens Park Rangers on Sunday if manager Jose Mourinho selects him, while John Obi Mikel should be ready to return for the Blues at Loftus Road. Diego Costa is expected to miss at least two weeks of action with hamstring trouble.

Andros Townsend scored a wonder goal for England in a friendly match against Italy, silencing his critics who had doubted his abilities. He was motivated by negative comments from people like Paul Merson, and he proved them wrong with his impressive performance. Despite a tough season, Townsend has the support of England's manager, Roy Hodgson, who kept faith in him. Townsend's goal helped his team earn a 1-1 draw against Italy.

A man who stabbed his cheating wife multiple times has written a letter from prison asking her to send him a suit for his trial. The wife, who was left with life-threatening injuries, sobbed in court as she testified that she never wanted to hurt her husband and that the affair was her fault. The husband, a former councillor and president of the local Royal British Legion, has pleaded not guilty to attempted murder.

The UK is set to open its first three proton beam therapy centres after cancer-stricken five-year-old Ashya King made a miracle recovery after receiving the treatment. The centres will be available to NHS cancer patients in Cardiff, London and Northumberland by 2017, with the first in Cardiff being operational by next year. The announcement comes just weeks after Ashya's parents revealed that he had been given the "all-clear" after receiving proton beam therapy at a centre in Prague. The treatment is highly targeted and aims radiation directly at the tumour, reducing the risk of damaging surrounding tissue and causing side effects. The UK currently sends patients abroad for proton beam therapy, with more than 400 patients having been sent abroad since 2008. The NHS will create two proton beam therapy units in 2018, but in the meantime, Proton Partners International has formed in the UK, with almost £100 million equity finance committed. The centres will provide conventional radiotherapy, chemotherapy and supportive care.

Ambulance bosses in the UK are recruiting paramedics from Australia because it is cheaper than training them in Britain. The London Ambulance Service has hired 225 paramedics from Australia and New Zealand in the last month alone, and plans to recruit more later this year. The selection process, which includes a practical demonstration and an interview, takes place at five-star hotels and applicants receive an email within hours of the interview to find out if they have a job. The exodus of paramedics from the UK is due to frustration at having to spend hours queuing outside A&E units and dealing with non-urgent calls from patients unable to see a GP. The cost of training one paramedic in the UK is £50,000, but it costs only £90,000 to recruit 200 paramedics from Australia, including flights and hotel bills.The

Chelsea have turned to the latest fitness technology to help them win the Premier League title. They have partnered with Technogym, a leading wellness solutions provider, to equip their Cobham training ground with state-of-the-art equipment. Players such as Eden Hazard and Nemanja Matic have been pictured working out, and the club's Twitter account has featured a video of young defender Kurt Zouma working out at Cobham. Technogym's founder and President Nerio Alessandri said that both Chelsea FC and Technogym share a strong dedication to performance, and they are proud to be selected as Chelsea FC's fitness equipment partner. Chelsea fitness coach Carlos Lalin has hailed the club's partnership with Technogym, and the club has had two players nominated for the PFA Player of the Year awards.

Babies are capable of understanding complex social situations and can comprehend what constitutes bullying, friendship, and being a bystander from the age of 13 months old, according to a study by psychologists at the University of Missouri. The study found that infants are able to form predictions about the world and use their existing knowledge to learn from unexpected situations. When babies are surprised, they learn much better, as they try to figure out what happened. The study also found that babies are sophisticated thinkers and have rich, sophisticated expectations about the world.

Manny Pacquiao trained on the streets of Los Angeles on Friday ahead of his highly-anticipated fight against Floyd Mayweather. He worked on his fitness and stamina, running around Griffith Park with his dog Pacman and showing off his skills by shadow boxing. Pacquiao also worked on his core strength during a training session on the mats. He revealed the multicolored mouth guard he will wear during the fight and demonstrated his confidence by the container it comes in. Pacquiao looked focused and determined as he prepares for the May 2 bout in Las Vegas.The

A cat named Biso was stuck in a wall at a Cairo train station for five years and was rescued by animal rights activists after a social media campaign. Biso survived thanks to an elderly man who fed him scraps of food every day. The cat was finally freed after workers removed a section of the wall, but Biso quickly ran away before anyone could catch him.

At least 35 workers were killed and a dairy factory was destroyed in an airstrike in Yemen as Saudi Arabian warplanes continue to target Shiite rebel positions in the country. The factory was also being used as a weapons cache, according to military officials. The airstrikes came as Saudi Arabia hinted at the possibility of a ground invasion in Yemen to force the Houthis to allow the return of the current president. The UN reported that 62 children were killed and 30 wounded in the fighting in Yemen over the past week. Protests against the airstrikes were held in Tehran, Iran, with demonstrators burning photos of Saudi King Salman and marching outside the Saudi Embassy.

A truck crash on an elevated highway in Boston caused delays for hundreds of morning commuters. The truck collided with a car on Interstate 93 southbound in the city's Dorchester neighborhood at about 6am, and both drivers were taken to hospital with non-life-threatening injuries. The collision caused headaches for locals trying to get to work, and replacement shuttle buses were run for southbound passengers with long lines forming. The truck driver was a 57-year-old Woburn man and the car driver was a 42-year-old Attleboro man, but no names were released. State troopers are still investigating the incident and no charges have been filed.The

Mark McCall, the director of rugby for Saracens, praised his young players after their loss to Clermont in the European Rugby Champions Cup. Despite the defeat, McCall has no intention of overspending in the upcoming transfer market and plans to wait for the right player to improve the team. The chairman of Saracens, Nigel Wray, had suggested that the team might sign a high-profile player from outside the league, but McCall said they would only do so if the player was the right fit for the team. McCall also noted that the young players in the Saracens pack could be the mainstay of the team for the next few seasons.

The bodies of the four alleged terrorists responsible for the Garissa University College attack were paraded in a pickup truck through the town of Garissa, Kenya, before being displayed at a primary school. Survivor Cynthia Cheroitich, who hid in a wardrobe during the attack, was rescued and taken to the hospital for observation. Four attackers died at the university, but their nationalities and identities have not been revealed. A total of 148 people were killed in the attack, with the gunmen shooting and beheading those who could not recite the Koran. Al-Shabaab has claimed responsibility for the attack and warned of more attacks in Kenya.

Arsenal must make a swift decision on Petr Cech this summer or risk losing out on the goalkeeper. Cech will leave Chelsea at the end of the season after losing his No 1 spot and is expected to hold talks with manager Jose Mourinho to confirm his decision. Arsenal is considering a move for Cech, but will face competition from Liverpool, Paris Saint-Germain, Roma, and Inter Milan. The Gunners must overcome the obstacles of Cech's valuation and Chelsea's reluctance to sell to a Premier League rival. Cech would consider moving to the Emirates Stadium, and hopes his long service with Chelsea will allow him to make the final decision on his next destination.

Sheik Joaan Al Thani has signed up Gregory Benoist to ride horses under his Al Shaqab banner in France, with the exception of dual Arc winner Treve, who will continue to be partnered by Thierry Jarnet. This move is seen as a snub for Frankie Dettori, who will now focus on the British flat season. Herbert, the racing manager for Al Shaqab, said that the decision was made due to the expansion of the operation, which now has 80 horses in France and almost 100 in Britain. Dettori finished third on Al Shaqab's Moheet in yesterday's Novae Bloodstock Craven Stakes at Newmarket, and both Ivawood and Estidhkaar could run in the Guineas. Retiring champion jump jockey AP McCoy rode his last race at Cheltenham and will not ride again until Sandown's end-of-season meeting on Saturday.The

Lois Lilienstein, a co-star of the Canadian preschool show "Sharon, Lois & Bram's Elephant Show" and a member of the singing trio, has died at the age of 78. She passed away from a rare form of cancer and was surrounded by her family. Lilienstein was born in Chicago in 1936 and moved to Toronto in 1996 with her son and husband. She joined Sharon Hampson and Bram Morrison to launch their singing trio in 1978. The TV show "Sharon, Lois & Bram's Elephant Show" ran on CBC in Canada from 1984 to 1989, before continuing in reruns on Nickelodeon stateside until 1995. Sally Catto, general manager, programming at CBC Television, paid tribute to Lilienstein for her contribution to Canadian kids TV.

This video shows French freediving champion Guillaume Néry jumping into the world's second deepest underwater sinkhole, Dean's Blue Hole in the Bahamas, without scuba gear and holding his breath. The footage shows him reaching the bottom of the 660ft hole and swimming back to the surface. The hole is the deepest so-called 'blue hole' in the world with an underwater entrance. Free divers are able to hold their breath for more than 20 minutes and must practice mind-body control techniques to push self-induced apnoea to the limits. Some free divers can hold their breath for more than 20 minutes, with Stig Severinsen holding the record for the longest time breath held voluntarily by a male. The video was filmed in 2010 by Néry's girlfriend and fellow freediver Julie Gautier.

A suicide bomber from ISIS blew himself up in front of a bank in Jalalabad, Afghanistan, killing at least 33 people and injuring more than 100 others. The attack was claimed by an ISIS offshoot called ISIS Wilayat Khorasan, and the group said the bomber was named Abu Mohammad and he belonged to their ranks. The Taliban distanced themselves from the attack, and the United Nations condemned the violence, saying it may amount to a war crime. Fears about ISIS involvement in the region have been growing this year, and the group has been recruiting in Afghanistan.

Laura Wells, a plus-size model and environmental scientist, has launched a new swimwear line in collaboration with Swimsuits For All's trend range, SwimSexy. The collection is made entirely of 100% recycled material and is inspired by the ocean, featuring coral reef scenes throughout. The swimsuits cater to every shape, with sizes ranging from 10 to 24, and include one and two-piece suits with zippers, criss-cross straps, plunging V-necklines, and high-waisted bottoms. Wells said the primary challenge was finding environmentally-friendly material while keeping prices affordable, but the result is a collection that is both fashionable and sustainable.The

The TrackYourDose app developed by Germany-based esooka records a user's personal radiation exposure, including exposure from changes in location and flights. The app uses a mathematical model developed by scientists and meteorologists from the Physikalisch-Technische Bundesanstalt (PTB) in Germany and the University Oulu, Finland. The app measures all relevant types of radiation, including neutron radiation produced in the atmosphere. Users enter their flight details and solar activity for the flight, which is inputted using a neutron monitor from the University of Oulu in Finland. The app tracks cosmic radiation from air travel, as well as gamma radiation and cosmic radiation on the ground. Medical examinations with ionizing radiation, such as X-rays or CT scans, also contribute to radiation exposure. The app measures the ambient dose equivalent in microsieverts (µSv). The total annual radiation exposure of a typical person in Europe is around 2,100 µSv, while the average annual radiation of a US citizen is around 3,000 μSv. Blue Bell Ice Cream has suspended operations at an Oklahoma production facility after it was linked to a foodborne illness that caused the deaths of three people. The company took this step "out of an abundance of caution" to ensure the safety of its products and to maintain the trust it has built with consumers over a century. The recalled ice cream product was not sold in retail locations and was shipped in bulk to institutional accounts in 23 states. The U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention recommended that consumers do not eat any Blue Bell brand products made at the Oklahoma facility and that retailers and institutions do not sell or serve them. The company will conduct a thorough examination of the Oklahoma plant to determine the exact cause of the contamination and plans to reopen it once the investigation is complete.

Jon Hamm, star of Mad Men, has been exposed for his involvement in a college hazing scandal from 1990, where he allegedly set fire to a pledge and beat him with a paddle. Hamm, who was 20 at the time, was a member of the Sigma Nu fraternity at the University of Texas at Austin. The alleged victim claimed that Hamm and other frat brothers hit him with a paddle 30 times and then lifted him off the floor by his underwear, causing great pain. The pledge was then subjected to two hours of brutal physical attacks as part of his fiery baptism into the fraternity. Hamm was eventually charged with assault in connection with the incident, but the charges were dismissed before he began his ascent to superstardom. The Sigma Nu fraternity was shut down in 1990 after the pledge's mother made her son's alleged assault public by going to the police.

The UK government has pledged to protect the Falkland Islands from "Argentinian bullying" after Argentina launched legal action against British companies exploring for oil off the islands. This follows a speech by Argentinian President Cristina Fernandez de Kirchner, which prompted the UK Foreign Office to summon her ambassador for a dressing down. Argentina has accused three British and two US companies of working without permission to explore for fossil fuels on the Argentine continental shelf. The UK Foreign Secretary, Philip Hammond, has said that the islanders have a perfect right to develop their oil and gas industry and that the UK will protect them from Argentinian bullying. The Argentine government has also threatened to block further oil exploration and to try to block the owners of the companies in Argentine courts.

A Delta Air Lines plane landed at LaGuardia Airport in New York City and was met by firefighters wearing full protective suits after an odor of smoke was reported by the crew. Emergency workers surrounded the plane and used a thermal imaging camera to locate a potential heat source. Passengers were kept on the plane for about 45 minutes while the situation was being investigated. A Delta Air Lines spokesperson said the odor of smoke was detected moments after the plane landed and the flight crew shut down both engines as a precaution. The plane was taken out of service for an inspection and any necessary maintenance. The safety of Delta's customers and crew is always the top priority.The

David Luiz has injured his hamstring and will be out for at least four weeks. To pass the time, he has changed his hairstyle to a man bun, which has become a source of amusement for his teammates. However, the injury is not a laughing matter for the team's manager, who will miss both legs of their Champions League quarter-final tie against Barcelona.

US President Barack Obama has stated that diplomacy is the best way to deal with Iran's contested nuclear program. He believes that a comprehensive, long-term deal like the one recently agreed upon with Tehran is the best option. Obama expects a "robust debate" on the deal in the United States and will keep Congress apprised of the "substance of the deal." Many of Obama's Republican opponents in Congress have been skeptical of a deal with Iran, but Obama has hailed the agreement as a "historic understanding." There are still many details to be worked out before the deal is due to be signed on June 30.

A 12-year-old girl with leukemia has been kicked out of her private Catholic school for poor attendance and academic performance. The school made accommodations for her illness, but they were not enough. The girl's mother says that the school is failing their child and that she was not skipping school to have fun, but because she was too sick to attend. The family has filed a complaint with the Office of Civil Rights. The girl is now raising money for St. Baldrick's to find a cure for childhood cancer.

Researchers have found that passive smoking affects plants too, which can take up nicotine from contaminated soil and plumes of smoke. This may explain why some spices, herbal teas, and medicinal plants have high concentrations of nicotine in them, despite none being allowed in insecticides. The study shows that peppermint plants can take up high concentrations of nicotine from contaminated soils, as well as taking in the drug from smoke. The researchers found that the widespread occurrence of nicotine in medicinal, spice, and food plants may, at least in part, be due to other nicotine sources apart from the illegal use of insecticides.

Two chameleons were filmed fighting for a female mate in Madagascar. The more aggressive chameleon chased the other out of the tree and along a concrete wall, biting him during the struggle. The defeated chameleon eventually escaped.The

Jack Cosgrove, a 20-year-old prop from Worcester Warriors, has agreed to join Edinburgh on a two-year deal. He has been capped nine times for the Scotland Under 20s team and is looking to add something extra to the squad. Cosgrove is eager to improve his game and learn from Alasdair Dickinson, an exceptional player in the same position. Edinburgh is currently in the European Cup final and has a strong buzz around the club.

Aaron Hernandez, a former NFL player and murderer, has been moved to the maximum-security Souza-Baranowski Correctional Center near Shirley, Massachusetts. He is being held separately from other prisoners and is on suicide watch. Hernandez was found guilty of murdering Odin Lloyd and was given a life sentence without parole. He was also reportedly using the drug "angel dust," a hallucinogenic known to cause violent outbursts and paranoia.

Manchester City manager Manuel Pellegrini has confirmed that the club is looking to invest in homegrown talent, which may mean that young players currently on loan, including Jason Denayer, will be brought back to the club to fill gaps in the first team squad. Celtic are keen to retain the services of Denayer, but face an uphill struggle as the Belgian defender falls into the category of homegrown players required by Premier League regulations.

Ander Herrera, a midfielder for Manchester United, wears his full name on the back of his shirt for superstitious reasons. He had a successful three-year spell at Athletic Bilbao and wants to continue using his full name to carry on that form. Herrera is superstitious and wants to keep using his full name following his good spell at Athletic Bilbao. He has forced his way into the starting line-up at Manchester United with a series of impressive displays and took his tally to seven goals in all competitions with his double in the win against Aston Villa. Herrera hopes to show a lot more emotion as Manchester United target silverware in the future.

Porto supporters gave their team a hero's welcome despite a 6-1 defeat in the Champions League quarter-final against Bayern Munich. The team bus was met with a cacophony of noise from proud Porto supporters. Star striker Jackson Martinez and Ricardo Quaresma were perplexed by the warm reception. Porto coach Julen Lopetegui admitted his side was beaten by a better team.

The BBC has been criticized for creating a computer game called "Syrian Journey" that simulates the difficult and often deadly journey Syrian refugees face as they try to flee their war-torn country. The game, which is available on the BBC website, allows players to make decisions about how to escape Syria and reach Europe, with grim outcomes including being sold to militia, being beaten and thrown into the Mediterranean, and being separated from family members. Middle East expert Chris Walker called the game "sickening," and Twitter users also reacted negatively to the game. The BBC has defended the game, saying it shows the choices faced by Syrian families and has achieved a high number of online hits.

Two bombing victims, Jessica Kensky and Patrick Downes, have opposed the death penalty for Boston bomber Dzhokar Tsarnaev, urging others to "overcome the impulse for vengeance." The couple, who lost limbs in the 2013 marathon attack, made their position highly emotional and practical. They join the Richards, who lost their son Martin in the blast, in calling for Tsarnaev to be sentenced to life in prison without parole to ensure he "disappears from our collective consciousness as soon as possible." The Richards oppose the death penalty for Tsarnaev, saying it would only bring continued pain for themselves and other bombing victims. Tsarnaev's lead defense attorney, Judy Clarke, is trying to paint her client as a gullible young man who was a secondary player in his older brother's terrorist plot.

Hamdi Ulukaya, the founder and CEO of Chobani, has settled a lawsuit filed by his ex-wife, who claimed half of the $2 billion Greek yogurt empire. The settlement came before a ruling on whether Giray could be named a shareholder in Chobani's predecessor company. Ulukaya's company was not an issue in their divorce, but Giray based part of her claim on handwritten notes her lawyers interpreted as evidence of financial support. Ulukaya's camp settled to avoid losing assets worth $1 billion to Giray. However, Chobani still faces business problems, including a product recall in 2013 that led to negative EBITDA of $87 million in the fourth quarter, and the company is considering replacing Ulukaya as CEO.The

Diego Costa has suffered a hamstring injury and will miss Chelsea's next two games against Queens Park Rangers and Manchester United. However, he is expected to be fit to face Arsenal on April 26, which could be a crucial game in the title race. Costa will not do any ball work this week, but will focus on strength sessions and intensive massages on the injured muscle. He will also see a specialist before stepping up his rehabilitation regime. Mourinho will not take any unnecessary risks with Costa and may decide against fielding him against Arsenal if the title is virtually sewn up. The club is considering giving Costa an extended break between now and the end of the season to help him overcome his hamstring problems.

The England C team, which is made up of non-league players under 23, is facing the axe as part of the Football Association's spending review. The team, which has been in existence since 1979, is managed by Paul Fairclough and selects players outside of the Football League. The FA is looking to save £30 million to fund its masterplan to reform grassroots football, and has identified the non-league national team as a potential area of saving. The team has only played a few games a year, but some of the friendly fixtures have attracted attention due to the elaborate travel involved. Some players who have played for the England C team have gone on to play for the full national team, but not for England. Former Leicester winger Steve Guppy holds the record for the ultimate one-cap wonder after winning one senior England cap after playing once for his country at non-league level.The

James Haskell, the London Wasps captain, dressed up as Iron Man and posted a photo on his Instagram page to promote the release of the new Avengers: Age of Ultron movie. The photo was taken at Westfield London shopping centre where the movie premiered, and Haskell was joined by other members of the A-list cast, including Robert Downey Jr., Chris Hemsworth, and Scarlett Johansson. Haskell returned to Wasps in 2012 after spending several years playing rugby in France, Japan, and New Zealand. Since his return, he has become a key player for both Wasps and the England rugby team, with over 57 caps to his name.

A woman on a Sydney train launched a racist tirade against a Muslim woman wearing a hijab, prompting Stacey Eden to stand up for the couple and record a video of the incident. The police have urged witnesses to come forward after Daily Mail Australia published the video. The Muslim couple was "very grateful" for Ms Eden's stand, according to her. The Islamophobia Register Australia group praised Ms Eden's actions and expressed disappointment in the woman's remarks. Incidents of abuse against Muslim women are becoming increasingly common, according to Mariam Veiszadeh, a hijab-wearing woman who was subject to a physical and verbal assault on a Sydney train last month.

Ursula Ward, the mother of Odin Lloyd, who was killed by Aaron Hernandez, is moving forward with a civil lawsuit against Hernandez. She wants to look him in the eye when he testifies during the trial. Hernandez, who was convicted of first-degree murder in Lloyd's death, will no longer be able to hide behind any Fifth Amendment rights against self-incrimination. The lawsuit, seeking unspecified damages, was filed in December 2013 but was put on hold during the criminal trial. The team was originally named in the suit, but the organization was dismissed after agreeing any money released to Hernandez would be granted to the Lloyd family. Britain has struck oil in the Falklands, a discovery that could escalate tensions with Argentina over the ownership of the islands. Argentina has threatened to prosecute oil companies operating off the Falklands coast, claiming they are acting illegally in Argentine territory. The discovery, made by British firms in a remote field of the islands, could be worth billions of pounds and increase fears of renewed conflict over the British overseas territory. The rhetoric and sabre-rattling from Argentina will grow, according to a former First Sea Lord, and the latest incident sees a heightening of tensions between Argentina and Britain over the Falklands.

A three-legged cat named Freeman was mauled to death by two dogs in a brutal attack captured on CCTV. The attack took place in the front garden of a home in Tarring, West Sussex, and was witnessed by a neighbor who passed the footage on to the cat's owner, Tracy Lynch. The 90-second attack shows the two dogs pouncing on Freeman and dragging him onto the neighbor's lawn before tearing into him. A woman is seen pulling up in a blue car and collecting the dogs, leaving Freeman to die in agony. The police are investigating the attack and the RSPCA has been informed. The cat's owner is devastated by the attack and the lack of action taken by the dog owners to check on Freeman's condition. The attack is described as "pretty horrific" by a neighbor who knew the cat well.The

A Chinese woman has become an internet sensation after posting pictures of herself with her pet pig, which she dresses, walks, and even sleeps with every day. The pig, named Five Flowers, has grown to a whopping 187lbs and sleeps in the same bed as the woman. The woman's husband is reportedly "tolerant" of the relationship, but the pet dog is envious of the attention the pig receives. The woman has almost 40,000 followers on Weibo and lives in Beijing with her husband, Five Flowers, a pet dog, and a rabbit.
